  ### 2. Analyzing JavaScript Type Behavior

  We analyze how the  IsPalinDrome  function handles an object rather than a string:

    const IsPalinDrome = (string) => {
        if (string.length < 1000) {
            return 'Tootus Shortus';
        }
        // ...
    
  If we pass a JSON object  {} , the property  string.length  is  undefined .
  In JavaScript:

  •  undefined < 1000  evaluates to  false .
  • This bypasses the first check.
  ──────
  ### 3. Evaluating the Loop

  Next, the function initializes an array using the length property:

    for (const i of Array(string.length).keys())
    
  With  string.length  being  undefined , this becomes  Array(undefined) .
  In JavaScript,  Array(undefined)  creates an array with one element:  [undefined] . Its keys iterator yields only the index  0 .
  The loop runs exactly once, where  i = 0 .
  ──────
  ### 4. Resolving the Indexes

  Inside the loop, the characters are compared:

    const original = string[i]; // string[0]
    const reverse = string[string.length - i - 1]; // string[undefined - 0 - 1] -> string[NaN]
    
  Because arithmetic operations with  undefined  result in  NaN ,  string.length - i - 1  resolves to  NaN .
  The comparison becomes:

    if (string[0] !== string[NaN] || typeof string[0] !== 'string')
    ──────
  ### 5. Constructing the Payload

  To prevent the function from returning an error:

  • Both  string[0]  and  string[NaN]  must exist.
  • Both must be strings.
  • Both must be equal to each other.

  This leads to the JSON structure:

    {
      "palindrome": {
        "0": "a",
        "NaN": "a"
      }
    }  

  We verify that the size of this payload is 34 bytes, which is well below the 75-byte limit.
  ──────
  ### 6. Writing the Command

  Finally, we package this JSON payload into a  curl  command targeting the endpoint:

  • We use  -X POST  because the application expects a POST request.
  • We add  -H "Content-Type: application/json"  to specify the JSON format.
  • We attach the payload using the  -d  option.

